**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- `path.join()` does NOT sanitize traversal sequences - it happily resolves `../` to parent directories
- URL encoding (`%2F` = `/`) can bypass naive string filters
- Double encoding and mixed separators (`....//`) bypass simple replacement filters
- Attackers can read `/etc/passwd`, `/etc/shadow`, AWS credentials at `~/.aws/credentials`, or `.env` files with database passwords

**SECURE VERSION**:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const path = require('path');
const fs = require('fs');

const app = express();

